                <note rend="inline" type="source">825.00 Revolutions/20: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Chile</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Culbertson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Santiago</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-09-05T08:00:00-04:00"
                            >September 5, 1931—8 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 9:25 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>105. I have just talked at the Moneda with General Vergara, Minister of War, who
                    has been made Commander in Chief of all armed <pb facs="1025" n="911"
                        xml:id="pg_911"/> lorees. He said that the Government is determined to
                    suppress the mutiny and that bombing planes and troops are now moving on
                    Talcahuano, Valparaiso, Quintero, and Coquimbo. He expects to attack rebels
                    today. Steps have been taken to protect oil supply of Standard Oil Company at
                    San Antonio. I have requested consular agents at Talcahuano, Chañaral, Coquimbo,
                    and Tocopilla to inform me promptly of any developments affecting Americans or
                    American property. Santiago is quiet.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Culbertson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
